:id 529926, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Martin Stynes"}), :year 2009, :venue "Comput. Meth. in Appl. Math.", :ncit 0, :string "Numerical Solution of Systems of Singularly Perturbed Differential Equations.. ", :doc-id "Numerical Solution of Systems of Singularly Perturbed Differential Equations. 2009  ,  "}, 942893 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 942893, :key "journals/isci/Bede08", :title "Note on \"Numerical solutions of fuzzy differential equations by predictor-corrector method\".", :abstract "In the present note it is shown that the examples presented in a recent paper by Allahviranloo et al., are incorrect. Namely, the ''exact solutions'' proposed by the authors are not solutions of the given fuzzy differential equations (FDEs). The correct exact solutions are also presented here, together with some results for characterizing solutions of FDEs under Hukuhara differentiability by an equivalent system of ODEs. In this way a new direction for the numerical solutions of FDEs is proposed.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 473063, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Barnabás Bede"}), :year 2008, :venue "Inf. Sci.", :ncit 37, :string "Note on \"Numerical solutions of fuzzy differential equations by predictor-corrector method\".. In the present note it is shown that the examples presented in a recent paper by Allahviranloo et al., are incorrect. Namely, the ''exact solutions'' proposed by the authors are not solutions of the given fuzzy differential equations (FDEs). The correct exact solutions are also presented here, together with some results for characterizing solutions of FDEs under Hukuhara differentiability by an equivalent system of ODEs. In this way a new direction for the numerical solutions of FDEs is proposed.", :doc-id "Note on \"Numerical solutions of fuzzy differential equations by predictor-corrector method\". 2008  "}, 769933 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 769933, :key "journals/cacm/BellmanBK65", :title "Numerical integration of a differential-difference equation with a decreasing time-lag.", :abstract "Systems in which variable time-lags are present are of common occurrence in biology. Variable flow rates are a common cause of these variable lags. At present no extensive body of knowledge exists concerning the effects which these variable lags can cause. Shown here is a method of reducing some differential-difference equations to ordinary differential equations which can then be studied numerically with ease. Subsequent study will deal with situations in which multiple-lags and lags dependent on the solution itself are present.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 413917, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Richard Bellman"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1372322, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "June D. Buell"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 322598, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Robert E. Kalaba"}), :year 1965, :venue "Commun. ACM", :ncit 24, :string "Numerical integration of a differential-difference equation with a decreasing time-lag.. Systems in which variable time-lags are present are of common occurrence in biology. Variable flow rates are a common cause of these variable lags. At present no extensive body of knowledge exists concerning the effects which these variable lags can cause. Shown here is a method of reducing some differential-difference equations to ordinary differential equations which can then be studied numerically with ease. Subsequent study will deal with situations in which multiple-lags and lags dependent on the solution itself are present.", :doc-id "Numerical integration of a differential-difference equation with a decreasing time-lag. 1965  ,  ,  "}, 2931693 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 2931693, :key "journals/na/ZivariPiranE10", :title "An efficient unified approach for the numerical solution of delay differential equations.", :abstract nil, :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1603047, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Hossein ZivariPiran"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 874681, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Wayne H. Enright"}), :year 2010, :venue "Numerical Algorithms", :ncit 5, :string "An efficient unified approach for the numerical solution of delay differential equations.. ", :doc-id "An efficient unified approach for the numerical solution of delay differential equations. 2010  ,  "}, 949518 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 949518, :key "journals/jacm/AndersonBV60", :title "A Numerical Method for Solving Control Differential Equations on Digital Computers.", :abstract "Frequently, as in missile control systems, linear differential equations are simultaneous with nonlinear but slower acting differential equations. The numerical solution of this type of system on a digital computer is significantly speeded up by approximating the forcing functions with polynomials, solving the linear equations exactly, and numerically integrating the nonlinear equations with Milne integration. Automatic interval adjustment is possible by comparing errors in the nonlinear integration. The interval selected is related to the shortest time constant of the nonlinear equations rather than the shortest of all the equations. With this system, both detailed transient response and steady state conditions are revealed with a minimum of machine time.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 1527232, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "William H. Anderson"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 944585, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "R. B. Ball"} #search_api.search_api.Author{:id 433885, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "J. R. Voss"}), :year 1960, :venue "J. ACM", :ncit 13, :string "A Numerical Method for Solving Control Differential Equations on Digital Computers.. Frequently, as in missile control systems, linear differential equations are simultaneous with nonlinear but slower acting differential equations. The numerical solution of this type of system on a digital computer is significantly speeded up by approximating the forcing functions with polynomials, solving the linear equations exactly, and numerically integrating the nonlinear equations with Milne integration. Automatic interval adjustment is possible by comparing errors in the nonlinear integration. The interval selected is related to the shortest time constant of the nonlinear equations rather than the shortest of all the equations. With this system, both detailed transient response and steady state conditions are revealed with a minimum of machine time.", :doc-id "A Numerical Method for Solving Control Differential Equations on Digital Computers. 1960  ,  ,  "}, 1082702 #search_api.search_api.Paper{:id 1082702, :key "journals/tc/Worland76", :title "Parallel Methods for the Numerical Solution of Ordinary Differential Equations.", :abstract "This correspondence studies various classes of methods, collectively known as block implicit methods, for the purpose of solving initial value problems in ordinary differential equations (ODE's) on a parallel processor. Modifications of the sequential procedures are discussed which allow these procedures to be used in a parallel mode. Both one-step and predictor-corrector type algorithms are examined.", :author (#search_api.search_api.Author{:id 903618, :first-name nil, :last-name nil, :full-name "Peter B. Worland"}), :year 1976, :venue "IEEE Trans. Computers", :ncit 0, :string "Parallel Methods for the Numerical Solution of Ordinary Differential Equations.. This correspondence studies various classes of methods, collectively known as block implicit methods, for the purpose of solving initial value problems in ordinary differential equations (ODE's) on a parallel processor. Modifications of the sequential procedures are discussed which allow these procedures to be used in a parallel mode. Both one-step and predictor-corrector type algorithms are examined.", :doc-id "Par